-- Mains — original descriptive questions with model answers + key points for
-- AI-evaluated practice (band feedback, not a fake-precise numeric score).
insert into public.mains_questions (paper, topic, question_text, word_limit, marks, model_answer, key_points, difficulty) values

('GS1', 'Green Revolution', 'Discuss the socio-economic impact of the Green Revolution in India.', 150, 10,
 'The Green Revolution (1960s-70s) transformed India from a food-deficit to a food-surplus nation through high-yield seeds, irrigation, and fertilizers, concentrated mainly in Punjab, Haryana, and western UP. It achieved near self-sufficiency in wheat and rice. However, its benefits were uneven: large farmers with capital for inputs gained disproportionately over small and marginal farmers, widening rural inequality. Regionally, eastern and rain-fed India lagged, deepening interstate disparity. Environmentally, it caused groundwater depletion, soil degradation from excessive fertilizer/pesticide use, and a shift toward water-intensive monocultures at the cost of crop diversity. Overall, it solved a food-security crisis but created new agrarian and ecological challenges still being addressed today.',
 '["Increased foodgrain production and self-sufficiency","Concentrated regionally in Punjab/Haryana/western UP","Benefited large farmers more than small/marginal farmers","Widened regional and rural inequality","Groundwater depletion and soil degradation","Shift toward water-intensive monoculture, loss of crop diversity"]',
 'medium'),

('GS1', 'Freedom Struggle', 'Examine the role of women in the Indian freedom struggle.', 150, 10,
 'Women played a significant and often under-recognized role in India''s freedom struggle. Leaders like Sarojini Naidu and Kasturba Gandhi provided political and moral leadership, while Sucheta Kripalani and others organized grassroots mobilization. Women participated actively in the Non-Cooperation and Civil Disobedience movements, courting arrest and boycotting foreign goods, and the spinning of khadi became both an economic and symbolic act of resistance. During the Quit India Movement of 1942, women ran underground networks and led local protests when male leaders were imprisoned. Despite limited formal political rights and social constraints of the time, their participation broadened the social base of the movement and laid groundwork for post-independence gender rights discourse.',
 '["Leadership roles: Sarojini Naidu, Kasturba Gandhi, Sucheta Kripalani","Active participation in Non-Cooperation and Civil Disobedience movements","Khadi/spinning as symbolic and economic resistance","Underground organizing during Quit India Movement 1942","Limited formal rights despite significant contribution","Legacy for post-independence gender rights discourse"]',
 'medium'),

('GS2', 'DPSP', 'Discuss the significance of the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) in ensuring social and economic democracy.', 150, 10,
 'The Directive Principles of State Policy, though non-justiciable under Article 37, are fundamental in governance and guide the state toward establishing social and economic democracy. They underpin welfare legislation such as minimum wage laws, free education (Article 21A/RTE), and rural employment guarantees (MGNREGA), extending the promise of Fundamental Rights into lived economic reality. Courts have progressively harmonized DPSPs with Fundamental Rights — from the rigid separation in Golaknath to a balanced view in Kesavananda Bharati and Minerva Mills, which held that neither Part III nor Part IV should have absolute primacy over the other. In this way, DPSPs act as the conscience of the Constitution, pushing the state toward substantive equality rather than merely formal legal equality.',
 '["Non-justiciable but fundamental in governance (Article 37)","Basis for welfare legislation: minimum wages, RTE, MGNREGA","Extends Fundamental Rights into economic reality","Judicial harmonization: Golaknath, Kesavananda Bharati, Minerva Mills","Balances individual rights with collective welfare","Pushes toward substantive, not just formal, equality"]',
 'hard'),

('GS2', 'Anti-Defection Law', 'What is the significance of the Anti-Defection Law? Discuss its limitations.', 150, 10,
 'The Anti-Defection Law, added via the 10th Schedule (52nd Amendment, 1985), aims to curb political instability caused by horse-trading and opportunistic floor-crossing by legislators. It disqualifies members who voluntarily give up party membership or vote against party whip, while permitting mergers involving two-thirds of a party''s members. Its significance lies in stabilizing governments and reinforcing party discipline. However, it has notable limitations: the Speaker, often from the ruling party, acts as the adjudicating authority, raising conflict-of-interest concerns; delays in Speaker''s rulings have undermined timely enforcement; and by binding legislators strictly to the party line, it can stifle intra-party dissent and independent judgment on merit. Reform proposals include shifting adjudication to an independent tribunal or the Election Commission.',
 '["Added via 10th Schedule, 52nd Amendment 1985","Prevents horse-trading and political instability","Speaker as adjudicating authority — conflict of interest concern","Delays in Speaker''s decisions undermine enforcement","Stifles intra-party dissent and independent judgment","Reform proposals: independent tribunal / Election Commission adjudication"]',
 'medium'),

('GS3', 'Monetary Policy', 'Explain the concept of Repo Rate and its role in controlling inflation.', 150, 10,
 'Repo Rate is the interest rate at which the Reserve Bank of India lends short-term funds to commercial banks against government securities. It is the RBI''s primary tool under its inflation-targeting framework (currently 4% +/- 2%). When inflation rises, the RBI increases the repo rate, making borrowing costlier for banks; this raises lending rates for businesses and consumers, reduces money supply and demand, and cools inflation. Conversely, lowering the repo rate makes credit cheaper, stimulating investment and growth during periods of low inflation or slowdown. However, transmission of repo rate changes to actual bank lending rates is often incomplete or delayed, limiting the tool''s real-time effectiveness, and monetary policy alone cannot address supply-side or structural causes of inflation.',
 '["Rate at which RBI lends to commercial banks","Key tool under RBI''s inflation-targeting framework","Higher repo rate → costlier borrowing → lower inflation","Lower repo rate → cheaper credit → stimulates growth","Transmission to actual lending rates often incomplete/delayed","Cannot address supply-side or structural inflation causes"]',
 'medium'),

('GS3', 'Climate & Food Security', 'Discuss the challenges to India''s food security due to climate change.', 150, 10,
 'Climate change threatens India''s food security through multiple channels. Erratic and delayed monsoons disrupt sowing cycles for rain-fed agriculture, which still covers a large share of cultivated area. Rising temperatures reduce yields of staple crops like wheat, particularly during critical grain-filling stages. Increasing frequency of droughts and floods causes production volatility and post-harvest losses. Groundwater depletion, worsened by heat-driven irrigation demand, compounds long-term sustainability concerns, especially in Green Revolution states. Policy responses include the National Mission on Sustainable Agriculture, promotion of climate-resilient and drought-tolerant crop varieties, micro-irrigation subsidies, and crop insurance schemes like PMFBY — but scaling these to smallholder farmers remains a persistent challenge.',
 '["Erratic monsoons disrupting rain-fed agriculture","Rising temperatures reducing wheat/rice yields","Increased frequency of droughts and floods","Groundwater depletion compounding irrigation stress","Policy responses: National Mission on Sustainable Agriculture, PMFBY","Challenge of scaling resilience measures to smallholder farmers"]',
 'medium'),

('GS4', 'Ethics Concepts', 'What is the difference between ''probity'' and ''integrity'' in public life?', 150, 10,
 'Integrity refers to an internal moral compass — consistency between one''s values, beliefs, and actions, regardless of external observation. It is a personal ethical trait. Probity, by contrast, is the demonstrated, observable practice of ethical conduct within public or institutional settings — honesty, transparency, and accountability in the exercise of public duties. While integrity is intrinsic and can exist privately, probity is inherently public-facing and often codified through conduct rules, codes of ethics, and institutional oversight mechanisms. A public servant may possess personal integrity, but probity requires that this integrity be actively and visibly demonstrated through fair, transparent, and accountable official conduct. Both are essential and mutually reinforcing for good governance and public trust.',
 '["Integrity: internal moral compass, consistency of values and actions","Probity: observable ethical conduct in public/institutional settings","Integrity is intrinsic/personal; probity is institutional/public-facing","Probity often codified via conduct rules and oversight mechanisms","Both essential and mutually reinforcing for public trust","Integrity without probity may remain invisible to the public"]',
 'medium'),

('GS4', 'Emotional Intelligence', 'Discuss the role of emotional intelligence in effective public administration.', 150, 10,
 'Emotional intelligence (EI) — comprising self-awareness, self-regulation, empathy, and social skill — is increasingly recognized as essential for effective public administration. Self-awareness helps administrators recognize personal biases that could distort policy decisions or interactions with citizens. Empathy enables more citizen-centric service delivery, particularly in sensitive contexts like disaster response or grievance redressal. Self-regulation supports composure and sound judgment during crises or high-pressure negotiations. Strong social skills aid in stakeholder management, coalition-building, and conflict resolution across diverse constituencies. While technical knowledge and IQ remain necessary for domain expertise, EI complements them by enabling administrators to translate policy into humane, effective, and trust-building action on the ground.',
 '["Self-awareness helps manage bias in decision-making","Empathy improves citizen-centric service delivery","Self-regulation aids composure during crisis management","Social skills support stakeholder negotiation and conflict resolution","Complements IQ/domain knowledge, does not replace it","Translates policy into humane, trust-building administrative action"]',
 'medium'),

('Essay', 'Technology & Humanity', 'Technology, ultimately, is a means to human ends, not an end in itself. Discuss.', 1200, 125,
 'Technology has always been an instrument of human aspiration — from the wheel to artificial intelligence, its value lies not in its own sophistication but in its capacity to serve human welfare, dignity, and freedom. Historically, transformative technologies like the printing press, electricity, and the internet have expanded access to knowledge, healthcare, and economic opportunity, embodying the principle that innovation is justified by the human ends it serves.\n\nHowever, when technology is pursued as an end in itself — optimized for efficiency, profit, or novelty without regard to human consequence — it risks becoming dehumanizing. The Industrial Revolution, while raising material output, also caused labor exploitation until social and legal reforms recentered it around human welfare. Today, automation threatens livelihoods even as it raises productivity; pervasive surveillance technologies, justified by security or convenience, can erode privacy and autonomy; and the digital divide risks excluding those without access from participating in an increasingly tech-mediated society.\n\nThe corrective lies in human-centered design and governance: policies that ensure technological gains are broadly shared, ethical frameworks that govern AI and data use, and a cultural commitment to treating efficiency and innovation as means, never as substitutes for human judgment and values. A society that worships technology for its own sake loses sight of the very purpose it was built to serve — the flourishing of human life. True progress lies not in what technology can do, but in what it lets us become as a more capable, more humane civilization.',
 '["Technology as historical enabler of human welfare (printing press, electricity, internet)","Risk of dehumanization when technology becomes an end in itself","Industrial Revolution as cautionary example: material gain vs labor exploitation","Modern risks: automation job displacement, surveillance/privacy erosion, digital divide","Need for human-centered design and governance/ethical frameworks","Conclusion: progress measured by human flourishing, not technological capability alone"]',
 'hard');
